:: loc-dougs-cabin {"position":"250,400","size":"150,100"}
The cabin is located behind the barn, nestled among a group of pine treets. The 'cabin' is more like a shed and seems to have been built from scavenged wood and metal siding.
There is no lock on the door or a locking mechanism of any kind. You can [[push the door open->loc-dougs-cabin-inside]].

[[Exit->loc-lancaster-machine-barn-driveway]]

:: loc-dougs-cabin-inside {"position":"400,400","size":"150,100"}
The inside of the cabin is simple but cluttered. Still, there is some organization to the chaos.

One corner contains a microwave and an old large refrigerator. There isn't any stove.
[[Look in the fridge->object-dougs-fridge]]
In another corner there is a futon lying on the floor, without a frame and clothes scattered around, some falling out of an old dresser. 

Another corner holds a large chair, an old television set and stacks of magazines and books. From where you are standing, you can see that that the magazines are mostly automotive repair guides and farming manuals, though some are clearly adult in nature. A large outdoor-use trashcan sits in the center of the space. 
[[Look in the trashcan->object-dougs-trashcan]]

The bed is empty.
The television is off. 

Turning back to the door, you find the ubiquitous Farrah Fawcett poster taped to the wall next to it. You never saw any of her movies...
<<return>>

:: loc-corn-maze {"position":"400,400","size":"150,100"}
The three-acre corn maze north of the main house has evolved beyond human planning, as countless footpaths to Doug's cabin and the machine shed have created a labyrinthine network through the stalks. Six figures stand guard throughout the field, supposedly scarecrows but wearing an odd assortment of human clothing—a woman's floral dress, a man's suit jacket with the sleeves cut off, children's winter coats in bright colors now faded by seasons of weather. Their faces are stitched burlap, but the expressions seem to shift when you're not looking directly at them. Sometimes, on still days, you can see them turning their heads to track your movement through the maze, their straw-stuffed limbs creaking softly in the absence of any wind.

You walk around a bit but get confused. There doesn't seem any point in continuing.
